Morphological diagnosis. Process of male tergite 9 high, perpendicularly elevated, 3 × as wide as epiproct sclerite ( Figs. 10, 13 ), rectangular, the membranous portion sides parallel in caudal view ( Figs. 13 , 21 ). Main epiproct sclerite (Ep-scl): narrow and acute in dorsal view (
Fig. 10
), tip upcurved in lateral view ( Figs. 11 , 20 ); ventral membranous section ends far before the base in lateral view, apical spines stout, distributed on membranous portion and a few also on the sclerite (
Fig. 20
). Male micropterous, ventral vesicle half as wide as the subgenital plate (
Fig. 12
).

Distribution and ecology. We describe this species on the basis of six males from a single population in the Komi Republic, Russia (
Fig. 22
). The type locality is a lowland forest stream, tributary of the Sysola River, Dvina drainage basin. Further populations of
Zwicknia
from European Northeast Russia (
Loskutova, 2003
) probably belong to this species, but the actual distribution of this species in the East European Plain or Russian Plain is unknown.
Zwicknia komica
and
Z. bifrons
from Norway (
Lillehammer, 1988
;
Boumans, 2011
) have the northernmost distribution of the genus.
